@NODE filename "Filename directions"

	Filename
	--------
  This refers to the file name of the text file you're going to convert into a maze. Please note 
the .html files are written in the path you're in when you start the program.

  @{"Back" link usage}

@ENDNODE

@NODE compass "Compass directions"

	Compass
	-------
  This puts a compass on each .html page, showing which way the user is "facing".

  @{"Back" link usage}

@ENDNODE

@NODE minimap "Minimap directions"

	Minimap
	-------
  Puts a 3x3 overhead map showing the next few steps in birds-eye perspective. I put it in for
debugging, but figured I should keep it.

  @{"Back" link usage}
  
@ENDNODE

@NODE mapfile "Mapfile directions"

	Mapfile
	-------
  Creates a file called map.html. This is an overhead map of the entire maze, with links to the
individual rooms.

  @{"Back" link usage}

@ENDNODE 

@NODE noinfofile "Noninfofile directions"

	Noinfofile
	----------
  By default, wolfhtml writes a file called "mapinfo.html" that displays the statistics for the map,
including how many .html files were written, the number of walls and floors in the map, and a link
to the map.html file. With the noinfofile option, this file isn't written.

  @{"Back" link usage}

@ENDNODE

@NODE htm "Htm directions"
	
	htm
	---
  This tells wolfhtml to link to .htm files instead of .html files. This is useful if you're
running your own webserver on an older dos-based system that only supports 3-letter file
extensions. The rest of the filename shouldn't be an issue, unless you have one hell of a 
huge maze.

  @{"Back" link usage}

@ENDNODE

@NODE norooms "Norooms directions"

	norooms
	-------
  This tells wolfhtml to not generate any room files. Usefull if you only want to generate the map
file, and can be used in combination with the @{"mapfile" link mapfile} and @{"noinfofile" link noinfofile} options.

  @{"Back" link usage}

@ENDNODE

@NODE maplink "Maplink directions"

	maplink
	-------
  This puts a map icon on the .html page which links to mapfile.html. Kind of a cheat, but might 
be useful I suppose.

  @{"Back" link usage}

@ENDNODE

@NODE gfx "Graphics formats"

	Graphics overview
	-----------------
  There are enough graphics files to run wolfhtml included in the archive, but in case you
want to add your own or edit the existing ones, these are some things you should know.

  Wolfhtml uses several different .gif images to render a "room", which is one view of the maze.
Rooms are named by room number, direction you're facing, and extension. EG, if your facing north
in room 26, the .html file you're looking at is 26n.html, while facing west would be 26w.html.
if you noticed, in the sample/ directory, there's a subdirectory called graywall/. In here are 13
.gif images that make up a view in a room. The numbers indicate how many steps back fromt he 
view the wall is, and the letters loosly translate into a perspective. The leading letter z stands
for "zone", which the answer to why is a mystery, as I came up with that after several hours of
typing code and slamming 2 liter bottles of Mountain Dew, plus some coffee :). Anyway, z1l.gif
simply means "zone 1 left". (1 step away from the viewer, angled wall on the left) z1s.gif is 
"zone 1 side". (1 step away from the viewer, flat side wall. no left or right needed) z1m.gif
is "zone 1 middle". (1 step away from the viewer, flat middle wall) I converted the .gif files
into icons, to make it easier to know which is which. If you make you're own images, try to keep
the file sizes the same. If you change the file sizes, at least mantain the aspect ratio for best
results. If you find a really easy way of rendering wall images, PLEASE!!!! @{"Let me know!!!" link contact}.
  In the root level of the sample/ directory, you might have noticed some more .gif files. These
are miscelleneous files used for various things.

	comps.gif, compn.gif, compe.gif, compw.gif
  These are compass pictures, for use with the @{"compass" link compass} option. They're just
pictures of a compass pointing in 4 directions. EG comps.gif is a compass pointing south, while
compw.gif is a compass pointing west. If you don't want a compass on your maze, you don't need
these in the same directory as your .html files.

	mlink.gif
  This is the image that appears when you use the @{"maplink" link maplink} option. Not needed if you don't want
to link to a map.

	left.gif, right.gif, up.gif
  These are the arrow buttons that the user clicks to navigate the maze. You'll want to keep
these.
  
  @{"Back" link main}

@ENDNODE

@NODE maze "Maze requirements"

	Maze requirements
	-----------------
	
  The original maze file is simply a text file, which uses '#' for walls, and ' ' (spacebar) for 
floors. It must be rectangular, and its best if the walls completly encircle the maze. Otherwise
you get some strange (and sometimes dead) links occuring. This would be a good maze.

@{"#" link mapwall}@{"w" link maptype}@{"graywall/" link mappath}@{".gif" link mapext}@{"|" link separator}@{"#" link mapwall}@{"*" link maptype}@{"wredwall/" link mappath}@{".gif" link mapext}@{"|" link separator}@{"#" link mapwall}@{" " link maptype}@{"ffloor/back" link mappath}@{".gif" link mapext}@{"|" link separator}@{"#" link mapwall}@{"n" link maptype}@{"wreddoor/" link mappath}@{"wredwall/" link mappath}@{".gif" link mapext}@{"|" link separator}
#################
#   *   *   *   #
# * * #   *   * #
#n* * ###########
# # * #         n
# # * ######## ##
#           #   #
# #########   n #
# n         #   #
#################
	
  Its rectangular, and completly "sealed-in". Also, to figure out how many .html files it'll
generate, take the number of floor tiles and multiply it by 4. If you have a larger size maze,
this will easily generate in excess of 1,000 .html files. (I would NOT recommend using a floppy
disk for this!)

  @{"back" link main}

@ENDNODE

