@NODE door "Door link files"

	Door link files
	---------------
	
  These files corrospond with the room numbers in the maze. If room number 103 is a wall, that
wall turns into a door, so when you walk into it, it goes to the url stated in the .dor file.
.dor files are all in ascii text, and limited to one line. The easiest way I know to create one
is open a cli, cd to your directory, and type:

echo "http://www.google.com" > 103.dor

  This creates a door when you create the maze. I would recomment a text editor that counts how
many characters into a file you're in, and subtract the lenght of the key part of the maze.
Failing that, its easier to just type:

wolfhtml map.maz mapfile norooms
  
  This creates a file called map.html, and won't generate any of the rooms, saving alot of time.
Open map.html in your web browser, find the number of your door (they're all listed over the
images), then edit the according .dor file.

  @{"back" link main}  
@ENDNODE   

@NODE install "Installation"

	Installation
	------------
  Pretty easy to install. I've compiled versions for:
68000
68020
68020 w/ FPU
68030
68030 w/ FPU
68040
68060

  Just find the one that matches your processor, and dump it into your path. (C: directory, S:, etc...)
Or put it somewhere else, and use its full pathname when you run it.

  @{"back" link main}
@ENDNODE

@NODE disclaimer "Disclaimer"

	Disclaimer
	----------
	
  I'm providing this as freeware, "as-is", and make no promises about its performance. 
It might eat your hard drive, it could crash your system, it might raid your fridge and
drink all your beer, it may hide every 5th sock it find in your dresser drawers, it migh
nag you to clean your room if it finds all your socks on the floor (OK, its late... 
I work second shift, and just got home.. sorry about the bad jokes.).
I've tested it, and it seems pretty stable on my system, though it might not be on yours.

  Seriously, though, I should warn that it CAN de-validate an FFS partition easily, if
it crashes during a disk write. Other than that, I'm not aware of anything harmful, 
though thats not to say I've missed something. If something DOES crash, please feel free 
to @{"contact me" link contact} with as many details about the crash you might have.
  
  @{"back" link main}
@ENDNODE